# llama-proxy.service — Host-first deployment systemd unit

## Overview

This systemd unit file runs the LLM proxy server (uvicorn-based) for the LLM
proxy stack. It is designed to be deployed as a **user service** (recommended),
though a system-service variant is documented below.

## User Service (Recommended)

This is the recommended deployment approach for single-operator setups. It
keeps the proxy process under the operator's login session, using the proxy's
built-in virtual environment.

**File location**: `~/.config/systemd/user/llama-proxy.service`

```ini
[Unit]
Description=LLM proxy server (OpenAI-compatible API)
After=network.target llama-server.service
Wants=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
WorkingDirectory=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/proxy
ExecStart=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/proxy/.venv/bin/python -m uvicorn proxy.server:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000
Environment=LLAMA_PROXY_CONFIG=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/proxy/config.yaml
Environment=LLAMA_START_SCRIPT=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/start-llama.sh

# Restart policy
Restart=always
RestartSec=5

# Logging
StandardOutput=append:/home/rgardler/.local/state/llama-proxy/logs/proxy.log
StandardError=append:/home/rgardler/.local/state/llama-proxy/logs/proxy.log

# Resource limits
MemoryMax=4G
CPUQuota=100%

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
```

### Setup commands (user service)

```bash
# Create log directory
mkdir -p ~/.local/state/llama-proxy/logs

# Enable and start the service
systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable llama-proxy.service
systemctl --user start llama-proxy.service

# Check status
systemctl --user status llama-proxy.service

# View logs
journalctl --user -u llama-proxy.service -f
```

## System Service (Alternative)

Use this approach only if the proxy must survive logout or run independently
of any user session. This requires root or sudo access.

**File location**: `/etc/systemd/system/llama-proxy.service`

```ini
[Unit]
Description=LLM proxy server (OpenAI-compatible API)
After=network.target llama-server.service
Wants=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
User=rgardler
Group=rgardler
WorkingDirectory=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/proxy
ExecStart=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/proxy/.venv/bin/python -m uvicorn proxy.server:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000
Environment=LLAMA_PROXY_CONFIG=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/proxy/config.yaml
Environment=LLAMA_START_SCRIPT=/home/rgardler/projects/llm/start-llama.sh

Restart=always
RestartSec=5

StandardOutput=append:/var/log/llama-proxy/proxy.log
StandardError=append:/var/log/llama-proxy/proxy.log

MemoryMax=4G
CPUQuota=100%

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
```

### Setup commands (system service)

```bash
# Create log directory
sudo mkdir -p /var/log/llama-proxy
sudo chown rgardler:rgardler /var/log/llama-proxy

# Install the unit
sudo cp llama-proxy.service /etc/systemd/system/
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable llama-proxy.service
sudo systemctl start llama-proxy.service

# Check status
sudo systemctl status llama-proxy.service

# View logs
sudo journalctl -u llama-proxy.service -f
```

## Verification

Regardless of deployment approach, verify the proxy is running:

```bash
# Check health endpoint
curl http://localhost:8000/health

# Expected response:
# {
#   "status": "healthy",
#   "ready": true,
#   "current_model": "gemma4",
#   "llama_server_running": true,
#   "backend_signals": { ... }
# }

# Check loaded models
curl http://localhost:8000/v1/models

# Check proxy logs
tail -f /home/rgardler/.local/state/llama-proxy/logs/proxy.log
# or for system service:
# sudo tail -f /var/log/llama-proxy/proxy.log
```

## Log paths

- **User service**: `$XDG_STATE_HOME/llama-proxy/logs/proxy.log` (typically `~/.local/state/llama-proxy/logs/proxy.log`)
- **System service**: `/var/log/llama-proxy/proxy.log`

